  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does garcinia cambogia actually work for weight loss?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The evidence is mixed. Garcinia cambogia contains hydroxycitric acid (HCA), which inhibits the enzyme ATP-citrate lyase that converts excess carbohydrates into fat. In theory, this should reduce fat storage. A 2011 meta-analysis in the Journal of Obesity analyzed 12 randomized controlled trials and found that garcinia cambogia produced "statistically significant but clinically modest" weight loss compared to placebo — approximately 0.88 kg (about 2 pounds) more than placebo over 2-12 weeks. This is a real effect, but small. Some studies show more significant results (3-5 kg over 8-12 weeks) when combined with caloric restriction and exercise. HCA also appears to increase serotonin levels, which may reduce emotional eating and improve appetite control. Garcinia cambogia is not a miracle supplement — it provides modest support that is most meaningful when combined with diet and exercise changes.' } },
