    <h2 id="why-garcinia">What the Science Says About Garcinia Cambogia and HCA</h2>

    <p>Garcinia cambogia (Garcinia gummi-gutta) is a tropical fruit native to Southeast Asia whose rind contains hydroxycitric acid (HCA) — a compound that has been studied for over 50 years for its effects on fat metabolism and appetite regulation. HCA's primary mechanism involves inhibition of ATP-citrate lyase, the enzyme responsible for converting excess carbohydrates (via citrate) into acetyl-CoA, the precursor for fatty acid synthesis. By blocking this enzymatic step, HCA may reduce the conversion of dietary carbohydrates into stored body fat, theoretically redirecting carbohydrate metabolism toward glycogen storage in muscles and liver instead.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">0.88 kg</span>
